{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Quickstart Rules\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 How to Play\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each player creates a player character (PC).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Gamemaster creates the rest of the world, playing out the characters, groups, and natural environment that challenge the player characters and provide the backdrop for them to spin their own story. Dramatic conflicts, such as feats of derring-do or swordfights, are resolved by each side rolling dice to determine success.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To play, you will need a copy of the Character Sheet and Combat Tracker for each PC, and a number of six-sided, eight-sided, ten-sided, and twelve-sided dice \u8211- six of each are recommended. You\u8217'll also need some sort of tokens such as glass beads or small coins to track each PC\u8217's status if a fight breaks out. Pencils, paper, and note cards (3x5 or similar) are useful too.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Creating a Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Creating a player character takes about 30 minutes to an hour, and can be done by the players separately before the game, or at the first game session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 For players:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before beginning to make choices and fill in the character sheet, think about what kind of character you\u8217'd like to make. Read over the background information and the classes, and have a concept in mind, as that can help you make decisions as you go through the character creation process.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you create your character, you\u8217'll be able to decide what she\u8217's good at \u8211- is she primarily a swordfighter or a negotiator? A cunning sneak or a bold ideologue? You\u8217'll want to remember that while this is a game with romance, intrigue, and diplomacy, it\u8217's also primarily a swashbuckling game \u8211- so you should also make sure your character can defend herself in a fight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 For the Gamemaster:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Tell your players a little about the type of stories that you\u8217'd like to tell, and if there are any particularly appropriate concepts or personality types that will work best in the scenarios you have planned, you can suggest those as well. However, don\u8217't be afraid to just let the players\u8217' creativity and imaginations run wild.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Attributes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each character is described by three Attributes that describe her basic strengths and weaknesses, as well as how she approaches life. Those Attributes are Verve, Affinity, and Guile, and they are rated either D6, D8, or D10.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A D10 in an Attribute indicates a high rating in that Attribute, while a D6 indicates a low score and D8 is average. During the character creation process, you get to choose one Attribute at D10, one at D8, and one at D6.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Verve\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character\u8217's Verve score measures her youthful exuberance, her gusto and gumption, her joie de vivre. Characters with a high Verve are aggressive in combat and off the battlefield as well, and usually favor a direct, brute-force approach to solving problems. Skill specialties related to Verve include Brawl, Lunge, Parry, Inspire, and Perceive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Affinity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Affinity is your character\u8217's ability to grasp how the world operates, both people and objects. Affinity includes a degree of intuition and natural ability at skills; characters with high Affinity are often builders, healers, or preservers. Aim, Treat, Intuition, Negotiate, and Husbandry are examples of Affinity skill specialties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Guile\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character\u8217's ability to think outside of the box is represented by her Guile: her cleverness, her ingenuity, her slyness, her brilliance. A character with high Guile often thinks in ways that bewilder or confuse others, and rarely favor the straightforward approach. The skill specialties Portents, Prowl, Deduce, and Deceive are related to Guile.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Competency Die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each character has a Competency Die that represents their general level of overall skill and life experience. New player characters begin with a D6 Competency Die; you can add your Competency Die to any skill check in which you\u8217're trained.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a character increases in experience, her Competency Die will slowly increase, as explained in the later section on Experience. A player character\u8217's maximum Competency Die is D12.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 For the Gamemaster:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can create non-player characters (NPCs) with no Competency Dice to represent untrained characters, or characters with higher Competency Dice to provide a greater challenge for experienced player characters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Skills & Specialties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are 12 Skills, ranging from Culture to Streetwise.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The basic level of training in a Skill is known as competency. If your character is competent with a Skill, you get to add your Competency Die to any rolls made with that Skill. Competency in a skill is represented by a checkbox on the character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once your character has competency in a Skill, you can also gain ranks in the Specialties for the Skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are three specialties for each skill, corresponding to the three Attributes: Verve, Affinity, and Guile. For example, the Specialties for Culture are Arts (Verve), Etiquette (Affinity), and Scholarship (Guile).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Specialties are ranked from +1 up to +5, although starting characters can only gain a maximum of +2. Each rank represents one additional die \u8211- of the same type as the Attribute die \u8211- that you can add to a dice pool when attempting that skill or specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} Your character has D10 for Guile, competency with Nature, and +2 ranks of the Prowl specialty. That means that you get to include your Competency die in your Nature (Prowl) roll, and you get to add 2 additional D10 dice (same size as your Guile die) to the pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Item Dice & Charmwoven Gear\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For certain skill rolls, you can add Item Dice to your pool, but only one die per roll. The most common item dice are Weapon Dice and Armor Dice, used in combat, but you can also get an Item Die for non-combat rolls if you\u8217're using tools, such as chirurgeon\u8217's knives or a crowbar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can also include one Charm Die in your roll. One common practice is the weaving of enchantments into fashionable clothing. These Charms assist you with specific Specialties by providing an extra die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A charmwoven cloak may give a Dodge D6 bonus, while a cavalier hat could provide Carouse D10.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} Because you envision your character sneaking around quite often, you buy yourself a piece of charmwoven apparel: boots that provide a Prowl D8 bonus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Making a Skill Roll\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The primary mechanic is the skill roll. You make a roll by gathering together a pool of dice and rolling them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your dice pool will consist of the following:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your relevant Attribute\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your Competency Die, if you\u8217're competent in the skill\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One die for each rank you have of the appropriate Specialty, matching the size of your Attribute die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One Item Die, if appropriate\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One Bonus Die, if appropriate\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You decide to use Prowl to get past a guard, so you start building your dice pool. Prowl is a Specialty of the Nature skill, and is associated with Guile.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The pool consists of:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab First, your Guile D10.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Then, because you\u8217're trained in Nature, you get to add your D6 Competency Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Next, your two ranks (+2) in Prowl give you two additional dice of the same type as your Guile Attribute, so 2D10.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab No Item Dice apply, but your +1D8 Charm Die on your boots applies as a Bonus die.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Thus your total dice pool for this roll will be 1D10 + 1D6 + 2D10 + 1d6.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To see if you successfully sneak, you will roll that pool of dice. This dice pool can be abbreviated as 3D10+1D8+1D6.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Reading a Skill Roll\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once you have rolled the dice, you need to read the results. You calculate your total by keeping the two highest-rolling dice and discarding all the rest. Add those two dice together for the total.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The lower die from the two you kept tells you the number of Success Points you rolled. If you succeed in your action, you can spend those Success Points to accomplish results.\par}
