{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Drop Penalties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Drop penalty is an adjustment to the number of dice you roll, based on a negative or hindering quality affecting your character. The most common Drop penalties are the results of Wounds, Combined Actions, Range Penalties, or General Modifiers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Drop penalties are expressed as \u8220"Drop X,\u8221" where X is the number of dice you must drop from your pool before rolling. \u8220"Drop 1\u8221" means to remove one die, \u8220"Drop 2\u8221" means remove two dice, and so on.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you drop dice, you get to choose which ones to drop. In nearly every situation you\u8217're going to be dropping your dice with the smallest size first, so D6 before D8, D10 before D12.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You have a dice pool to roll for Prowl: 3D10+1D8+1D6. However, you are suffering two Wounds, giving you a Drop 2 penalty. You drop the D8 and the D6, leaving 3D10.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You roll those dice, getting the following results:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 :::: dice ::::::::::::; | Die | Result | | :\u8211-: | :\u8212--: | | D10 | 2 | | D10 | 3 | | D10 | 7 |\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These total to 10, with three potential Success Points. :::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Opposition Dice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Whenever you make a Skill Roll of any kind, you are making an opposed check \u8211- either against an opponent or against Standard Opposition dice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When facing an opponent \u8211- such as trying to negotiate against someone or stab them with a sword \u8211- the opponent gets to make an appropriate defense or opposition roll. This is dependent upon the situation; for a Negotiate roll, the appropriate opposition is likely another Negotiate roll, while a Lunge can be opposed by a Parry, Block, or Dodge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 :::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::: example ::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::; {\i Example:} While Prowling around, you fail a roll and are spotted by a guard. She demands to know what you\u8217're doing and if you\u8217're supposed to be there. You aren\u8217't actually supposed to be there, so you need to make up a story to convince her. This requires the use of the Deceive specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Deceive is a Guile specialty under the Interaction skill, and you\u8217're competent with Deceive. You have 1 rank in the Deceive specialty. In addition, you have a charmwoven hat with a Deceive +1D6 Charm Die. Your dice pool is 1D10 + 1D6 + 1D10 + 1D6, or 2D10 + 2D6.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The opposition dice will be the guard\u8217's Intuition roll. The guard has an Affinity of D10, a D6 Competency Die, and +1 rank in Intuition. Her dice are 1D10 + 1D6 + 1D10, or 2D10 + 1D6.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You roll 2D10 + 2D6 and get 9, 3, 2, 3 for a total of 12 with three success points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Gamemaster then rolls for the guard\u8217's Intuition specialty and gets 6, 2, and 5. Her total is 11 and her success points are five.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Because her total is lower than yours, you succeeded on your Deceive roll and she buys your story. :::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Standard Opposition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are making a roll which isn\u8217't opposed by another character (PC or NPC), the Gamemaster will roll Standard Opposition dice \u8211- such as if you are walking a tightrope, picking a lock, or reciting a poem.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The number of Standard Opposition dice is always three, but the type of dice vary depending on the difficulty level set by the Gamemaster.\par}
