{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can spend your Success Points and achieve the desired results. Each \u8220"+\u8221" indicates the expenditure of one Success Point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The results you can achieve are dependent upon the shared reality of the fictional world. In other words, if there\u8217's no way you can convince the guard that your lie is true \u8211- for example, if you told the guard that you\u8217're her sister and she clearly knows her own family \u8211- then you can\u8217't choose to appear trustworthy. A Deceive roll isn\u8217't mind control!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If applicable and appropriate, you can choose a result more than once. It doesn\u8217't make sense to appear sincere twice, so you can\u8217't choose that multiple times, but if you had the success points you could gain mutiple style points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It\u8217's possible that you may run out of things to spend Success Points on. In such a case, the extra points you don\u8217't spend are simply unused and go away.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You have three Success Points and succeeded on your Deceive roll. You decide to spend your Success Points as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b +:} Think on Your Feet \u8211- you quickly come up with a good lie. \u8220"I\u8217'm the \u8230? inspector! I\u8217'm here to inspect \u8230? all the things!\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b ++:} Appear Sincere \u8211- you don\u8217't seem like you\u8217're obviously lying, so the guard believes you.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Style Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Style Points are a limited resource which you can use to improve your dice rolls. You start each game session with one Style Point and can gain more by spending Success Points with successful skill rolls. Three Success Points will earn you one Style Point. However, you can only have a maximum of three Style Points at any time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You score six Success Points on a Deceive roll, and spend your Success Points like this:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b +:} Think on Your Feet\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b ++:} Appear Sincere\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b +++:} Gain 1 Style Point\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Every time you gain a Style Point, you are required to describe what your character has done that is particularly stylish. You can\u8217't overly bend the narrative of the game \u8211- your stylish description can\u8217't have any mechanical effect \u8211- but you can use the opportunity to make your character perform an impressive act that is unique to her personality and style.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You choose to Think on Your Feet, Appear Sincere, and Gain 1 Style Point. The Gamemaster asks you, \u8220"what do you do that\u8217's so stylish while you\u8217're tricking the guard?\u8221" You answer:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"I give a dashing and reassuring smile as I tell this outlandish lie, a sparkle of moonlight reflecting off my teeth with a \u8216'glint!\u8217' sound. With confident assurance, I tell her that I\u8217'm here to perform an inspection, and I even hint that if she doesn\u8217't comply, she may be in trouble with her superiors.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Awesome! That happens,\u8221" says the Gamemaster. And you earn your Style Point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 For the Gamemaster:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It\u8217's perfectly within your rights to veto any stylish description if you think it\u8217's too absurd, but most of the time you should let players get away with whatever they want to describe. It\u8217's their Style Point and thus their chance to narrate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The only time that you should definitely step in is when you feel a description isn\u8217't stylish {\i enough.} Then you can prompt the player for more awesomeness and encourage them toward an over-the-top, flamboyant display.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Style Maneuvers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each player character starts with two Style Maneuvers and can purchase more with Experience Points. Style Maneuvers each cost one or two Style Points to use.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike {\i gaining} Style Points, you are not required to narrate something stylish when you {\i use} a Style Maneuver (but you can if you want to!).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are three types of Style Maneuvers: Maximize, Reroll, and Add.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Maximize (Specialty)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This Style Maneuver lets you spend two Style Point, then take one of the Specialty Dice of the appropriate Specialty and set that die to its maximum value before rolling. You don\u8217't roll that die, just set it to its highest value and set it aside, then include it after you roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can only have one maximized die in any given skill roll. (You can\u8217't spend two Style Points and maximize two dice.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You have the Style Maneuver \u8220"Maximize Deceive.\u8221" You can spend two Style Points to set one of your D10 dice to its maximum value before rolling. That gives you an automatic 10 on that die. You then roll the other dice \u8211- 1D10 + 2D6 \u8211- getting a 2, a 3, and a 2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Adding the 10 to the 3, you get a total of 13 with three success points. Nice!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Reroll (Skill)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This Style Maneuver lets you reroll a roll that you just made. Spend a Style Point, pick up all the dice (except maximized dice, of course) and reroll them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can reroll the same skill roll as many times as you like, until you run out of Style Points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You make your Deceive roll and get 4, 2, 3, and 2. That\u8217's really low \u8211- a total of 7 with 3 success points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You have a Style Maneuver \u8220"Reroll Interaction.\u8221" You spend a Style Point and reroll the dice, and get a much better roll: 7, 9, 2, 6. Hooray! This is a total of 16 and seven Success Points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Add (One Specialty) to (Another Specialty)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This Style Maneuver lets you add your Specialty dice to another roll. You add only the Specialty dice \u8211- of the same size as the first Specialty\u8217's related Attribute.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can only use each Add Style Maneuver once per roll, although you could use additional, different Style Maneuvers together on the same roll if they all apply.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You have a Style Maneuver that lets you add your Banter dice to your Deceive roll. Normally your Deceive roll is 2D10 + 2D6. You have +2 ranks in Banter (a Verve specialty), and your Verve is D8, so you get to add 2D8 (not your entire Perceive dice pool) to your Deceive roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your Deceive dice pool is now 2D10 + 2D8 + 2D6. You roll the dice and get 4, 9, 8, 2, 4, and 3. Hooray! This is a total of 17 and eight Success Points.\par}
