{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 XP and Competency Die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Experience points can be spent between game sessions, at the beginning of a session, at the end of a session, or between scenes. You can\u8217't spend your experience points during a scene, however.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 For the Gamemaster:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The XP system is flexible and relies on your judgment as to how many points to award per session, although the default is three XP to five XP for a typical session of four hours of game play. In general, you should only give out XP at the end of a session, not immediately after each scene.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Character Creation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Summary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To make your own character, follow these instructions while filling out the character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Competency Die, XP, & Yield Limit\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a starting character, you have a D6 competency die and you start with 0 XP earned, 0 XP spent. Your Yield Limit equals the maximum value of your Competency Die plus 3, so 9 for a starting character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Choose Two Classes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character is a composite of two classes. For each class chosen, record the following information:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Skills & Specialty Ranks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your classes determine your starting Skill Competency and your Specialty ranks. For each skill listed, check the corresponding box to indicate Competency. For each Specialty listed, place a +1 in the appropriate blank space; if both classes give ranks in a specialty, write +2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Weapon & Armor Prowess\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your Weapon prowess & Armor prowess are the total of those granted by your two classes. Check the boxes on the character sheet that correspond with all of your Weapon and Armor prowesses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Social Rank & Wealth\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For each of your classes, record the Social Rank and the die for each rank. For example, if your two classes give the social ranks Commoner (1D0) and Soldier (1D6), you\u8217'd write down \u8220"Commoner (1D0)\u8221" and \u8220"Soldier (1D6).\u8221" Also record the dice values on the Wealth section of your character sheet, along with your Competency Die. Your total Wealth Roll consists of those three dice together in a pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The social ranks are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Commoner (D0)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Soldier (D6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Artisan (D8)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Noble (D10)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Royalty (D12)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Bonus Gear\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each class provides you with a set of clothing and possibly additional equipment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Style Maneuvers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Choose one Style Maneuver from each class and record it on your character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Attributes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your attributes are Verve, Affinity, and Guile. Assign one of them the value D10, another one D8, and the last D6, and write those in the appropriate boxes. You probably want to put the D10 in the attribute that corresponds to the column where you have the most Specialty ranks, but it\u8217's not required.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Nationality & Languages\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Choose and record your nationality.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are from France, you speak and read France; if not, you speak your native language automatically and don\u8217't know France (you\u8217'll need to learn it with one of your customizations; see step 10). For each prowess rank you have in Culture (Scholarship), you speak and read an additional language. Record each language that you know.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Passions & Personifications\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Choose four Passions for your character that describe what she feels is important in her life. The standard Passions are Artistry, Church, Country, Faith, Family, Friends, Justice, Knowledge, Love, Loyalty, Lust, Pride, and Wealth. You will rank your four chosen Passions from D12 (the strongest) to D6 (the weakest).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Optional:} For each Passion, name one person associated with that passion and record that person\u8217's name to the right of the Passion. This is the person (living or dead) whom your character most closely associates with that Passion, either positively or negatively. You can use an existing NPC (or even PC), or name a new one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Customizations\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You get to choose up to six customizations for your character. Choose your six customizations from the following list (you can choose each customization more than once):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Increase one of your Social Rank values by one step; you can increase each Social Rank die only once.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add one Weapon or Armor Prowess.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add a new Language.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add one Skill Competency.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add +1 rank in a Specialty, to a maximum of +2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add a Style Maneuver from either of your classes or from your Nationality.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Additional Equipment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You begin with bonus gear as determined by your class listings. You also get your choice of one weapon: Knife, Pistol, or Sword.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You begin the game with three Rewards \u8211- one of them equal to your Competency Die, and the other two equal to your Social Rank Dice. You can buy additional equipment by using these Rewards \u8211- for example, a D8 Reward can be used to purchase any item of cost D8 or lower.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you don\u8217't want any of your starting gear, you can sell it back and gain an equivalent Barter Die. For example, if you don\u8217't want a musket (Cost: 1D10), you can trade it in for one D10 Barter Die. You can\u8217't make any Purchase rolls or use your Barter Dice during character creation, but you can spend your Rewards.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Character Details\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Write down a name, gender, and other biographical data for your character. Write down two or three words for your character\u8217's Reputation, such as \u8220"Fearsome Opponent,\u8221" \u8220"Mostly Harmless,\u8221" or \u8220"Renowned Lover.\u8221" Your reputation need not be true.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Passions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters in this game are passionate, and their passions often spur them on to fantastic success or dismal failure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each character is defined by four Passions that are ranked with Passion Dice, from D12 at the highest, down to D10, D8, and D6 at the lowest. The size of each Passion Die indicates the relative strength of that Passion in the character\u8217's life.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You must always have one passion at D12, one at D10, one at D8, and one at D6, and they must all be different Passions. (You can\u8217't double up with the same Passion with two different dice sizes.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In addition, each of your Passions is embodied by another character, living or dead, as the Personification of that Passion in your character\u8217's mind.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Using Passions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can use your character\u8217's Passions when roleplaying, by making decisions that reflect the role her Passions play in her thoughts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In addition, Passions can also be used with Style Points for game benefits. Passions can be used in one of three ways:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Indulge your Passion during a scene to gain 1 Style Point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add your Passion die to a roll by spending 1 Style Point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Struggle with your Passion to make it harder for you to succeed at something \u8211- and when you fail, you gain a free Style Point.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Indulge Your Passion\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During a scene, if your character takes the time to focus on her Passion to the exclusion of other activities, you can gain 1 Style Point \u8211- but only up to the normal maximum of three Style Points at any one time. You can only do this once per Passion, per session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, someone whose Passion is their Faith may engage in prayer, while another person who has a Passion for Knowledge may engage in scientific discovery or reading a new book.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As with any time in which a Style Point is gained, you must describe how your character is acting with style.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Add Your Passion Die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By spending a Style Point, you can add one Passion Die to a Dice Pool under the following conditions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your Passion must be related to the roll that you are making.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You have not already added that Passion to a die roll in this session.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You need to have a good reason why your success or failure hinges on your character\u8217's Passion \u8211- for example, perhaps your character is motivated to succeed because of her sense of Pride, or her desire for more Wealth. If you can\u8217't justify how your character\u8217's Passion would influence the outcome, you can\u8217't spend the Style Point and can\u8217't include your Passion Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Struggle With Your Passion\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes your character\u8217's Passion isn\u8217't a benefit, but is a hindrance. In such cases you can choose to struggle with that Passion by adding the appropriate Passion Die to the opposing Dice Pool when the Gamemaster makes a dice roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your roll then fails, you gain 1 Style Point and get to describe how your character\u8217's Passion conflicted her and caused her to fail. If your roll succeeds, you don\u8217't gain this Style Point.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can only choose to do this when the roll is related to your character\u8217's Passion, as with adding the Passion Die to your own roll; in addition, you can only do this once per Passion per session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Inverted Passions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes, one\u8217's love for something can be twisted into pain. These are known as inverted passions; rather than being passionate toward the object of your Passion, you\u8217're opposed to it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You decide when you select a Passion whether it\u8217's normal or inverted. You probably shouldn\u8217't have more than one inverted Passion for a starting character, although your Passions may become inverted during the course of game play. (See \u8220"Changing Passions\u8221", below.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 List of Passions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following is a list of the most common Passions that drive characters in the game. You can pick from this list or write your own custom Passion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Several of these Passions require additional definition, such as specifying the Country that you\u8217're passionate about, or the group you\u8217're loyal to. You can record this beside the Passion die on your character sheet\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Artistry\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A character with a Passion for Artistry is drawn toward things of beauty, be they works of art, music, science, or nature. Such characters are often either artists themselves, or patrons of the arts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Artistry, Inverted:} The ugliness of your soul drives you to destroy things of beauty rather than cherish them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Church\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A character with a Passion for the Church is devoted to the hierarchy of a religious institution.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Church, Inverted:} You despise all that the Church stands for, seeing them as one of the greatest threats to your life and those of others.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Country\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Passion for one\u8217's Country is usually, although not always, the same as a Passion for the ruler of that country. The Passions may conflict if one has Loyalty toward one group or cause who opposes the current government.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Country, Inverted:} Your country has done you wrong \u8211- either through deliberate malice or \u8220"benign\u8221" neglect. Your ire may be directed against all people of that nation, or just against the ruling parties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Faith\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As contrasted with Passion for the Church, Passion for one\u8217's Faith is less about the religious organization and more about the beliefs. It\u8217's possible (and quite common) to have both Passions, or also to have just one or the other.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Faith, Inverted:} You reject the Faith that once filled your heart with joy. No longer a true believer, you work to convert others to leave that religion just as you have.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Family\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Characters with strong familial ties have a Passion for Family. This can include one\u8217's extended family and household, or may just be one\u8217's immediate family \u8211- such as parents or children.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Family, Inverted:} You\u8217're the one decent person in a family of terrible people \u8211- or perhaps the only terrible person in a family of saints. You\u8217're determined to prove to your kin that they were always wrong about you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Friends\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some people are very faithful to their Friends and would do anything for them \u8211- even die for them in some cases. You can decide if this applies to all your character\u8217's friends or just her closest friends.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Friends, Inverted:} You keep to yourself and don\u8217't form any friendships. Why? Because at one time in the past, you felt horribly betrayed by someone you trusted, and it\u8217's hard for you to call anyone \u8220"friend\u8221" again, no matter how nicely they\u8217're acting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Justice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The cause of Justice is a higher calling to right that which is wrong in the world. The Passion may stem from an innate sense of right and wrong, but more commonly it is a reaction to some act of terrible injustice that has been perpetrated against the character or the ones she holds dear.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Justice, Inverted:} The concepts of fairness and justice are a lie designed to keep us all docile sheep. Flaunting the law through blatant displays of criminal activity is your favorite way to subvert the status quo.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Knowledge\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Dedication to the pursuit of Knowledge can be expressed through a desire to learn the truth behind mysteries, to explore the world, or to learn all that can be learned.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Knowledge, Inverted:} There are some things that the common people were not meant to know. Only you can be fully trusted with these secrets, and you\u8217'll do what\u8217's necessary to stop that Knowledge from falling into the wrong hands.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Love\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Romance is the most common expression of a Passion for Love, although there are other types of Love that qualify. Love may be for a single person, or someone\u8217's heart may be divided among many loves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Love, Inverted:} Love hurts, scars, wounds, and marks. You knew you\u8217'd never love that way again, and now you\u8217're all out of love. All you want is someone who won\u8217't hurt you, won\u8217't hurt you no more. But does that person even exist?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Loyalty\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Passion of Loyalty is about dedication to a specific person or group. You must specify who is the subject of your character\u8217's Loyalty if you choose this Passion. You might not actually like the people you\u8217're loyal to, but this isn\u8217't about friendship but honor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Loyalty, Inverted:} You can\u8217't trust anyone. They might demand your loyalty or pledge it to you, but no one is actually faithful. Be on guard, for anyone may betray you at any time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Lust\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Passion of Lust is about following one\u8217's baser desires, usually expressed through sexual pleasure. Characters who are Passionate about Lust can be flirty, teasing, or promiscuous.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Lust, Inverted:} Actually, it\u8217's about ethics in sexual relationships. You\u8217're one of the good people, and yet the objects of your desire keep gravitating away from you and toward inferior mates! They\u8217'll pay for making you involuntarily celibate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Pride\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Passion for Pride means a character is highly focused on her own dignity and reputation. Affronts to such Pride are met with strong challenges, as such things are not to be tolerated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pride, Inverted:} Life feels like a succession of failures, but that\u8217's okay \u8211- you deserve such misery, right? The best you can hope for is to scrape by, surviving. Sure, it would be really nice if things turned around, but how likely is that to happen?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Wealth\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Individuals with a Passion for Wealth are focused on the acquisition, maintenance, and spending of sums of money. Some come from poor backgrounds and wish to move beyond their humble beginnings, while others are rich misers who count every penny.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Wealth, Inverted:} Money? Who needs money? It just leads to temptation. You give all of yours away as soon as you get it, usually to worthy charities or individuals. You might even steal from the wealthy to give to the impoverished.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Personifications\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Personification is someone who represents, to that character, the associated Passion \u8211- for good or for ill.\u160?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, someone with a Passion for family may think of her beloved mother who taught them how to hunt \u8211- or she could think of her overbearing grandfather who always demanded more than she could provide. Someone with a Passion for Country could be intensely loyal to the King himself, or could idolize a revolutionary writer from last century.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Personifications are a way to tie your character to the world and provide the Gamemaster with non-player characters for you to interact with. A Personification could be living or dead, an existing NPC or a completely new one created by the player.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Gamemaster\u8217's Toolbox: Passion Rolls\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In addition to using Passions to earn or spend Style Points, you can have players make a Passion Roll at the beginning of a game session. Such rolls give hints as to what is on the character\u8217's mind at the moment and a way to challenge that character\u8217's motivations in a meaningful way.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To make a Passion Roll, a player rolls all of the dice for her Passions \u8211- a D6, a D8, a D10, and a D12. The die that rolls the highest indicates which Passion is in play for that session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} Dani has the following Passions: Loyalty D12, Pride D10, Country D8, Love D6. She rolls her Passion dice, getting these results:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 D12: 5, D10: 7, D8: 6, D6: 3\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The high roll is the 7 and it\u8217's on the D10. Her D10 Passion is Pride, which means that Dani may face a situation where her Pride is tested.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 One of the simplest things to do is to have the player\u8217's Personification of that Passion make an appearance, or a story hook related to that Personification. In some cases it may not be possible \u8211- such as a long-dead grandparent \u8211- but even then, it pays to get creative. Maybe the character finds a long-lost letter, meets up with an old enemy of her grandparent, or even has a portentious dream about her ancestor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Passion Roll is a tool for improvising roleplay and shouldn\u8217't be seen as a constraint on your storylines \u8211- you can make the result of the roll as important or unimportant as you wish.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If your style as a Gamemaster runs toward planning instead improvisation, you can have your players make Passion rolls at the end of a game session and use the results to decide what plot elements to introduce in the next game.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In an ongoing campaign, it\u8217's likely that the same Passion will come up repeatedly. You can ameliorate this effect by removing from the pool the die corresponding to whichever Passion came up in the immediately previous session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Changing Passions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 During your character\u8217's life experiences, her priorities may change. After a game session you can make one of the following changes based on what happened during that session:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Swap two \u8220"adjacent\u8221" passions, such as your D12 Passion and your D10 Passion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Invert one of your Passions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Revert one of your inverted Passions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Change out your D6 Passion for a Passion you don\u8217't already have.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you swap, invert, or revert your Passions, your Personifications may or may not change; it\u8217's up to you to decide.\par}
