{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Optional Rule: Training Time\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each XP spent typically requires one week of practice or training. This requirement can be waived by the Gamemaster if you\u8217've already invested time and effort in activities relevant to your XP expenditure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Classes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character is a composite of two classes. Each class provides you with half of your starting skill competencies, specialties, weapon and armor prowess, social rank, starting gear, and style Maneuvers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The various classes can be divided up into three basic categories: skilled classes, social classes, and fighting classes. These are shown on the following tables.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For the most well-rounded character, choose a fighting class and either skilled or social class; that way, you\u8217'll be effective in a fight as well as outside of one. Duelist is a good choice for a fighting class, if you can\u8217't find another that doesn\u8217't really fit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are mainly interested in creating things or helping people, you can choose one skilled class and one social class, or two skilled classes.\par}
