{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Variants: Alternatives to Classes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You don\u8217't have to make your character with classes; here are two options that you can try, with your Gamemaster\u8217's permission!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Option: Playing Without Classes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You don\u8217't even have to play with classes (or backstories) at all. The MJ might allow this option if she wants everyone to have the most flexibility in creating their characters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A base character starts with the following:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Skill Competency in Defense, Initiative, Interaction, and Observation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One language.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Knife Weapon Prowess.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Social Rank of Commoner (D0)/Commoner (D0).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One outfit and one common weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 30 customizations, replacing the 6 customizations that characters normally receive.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can use those customizations in the following ways:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add Competency in any one skill.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add +1 rank to any Specialty which you have the related skill competency. Limits: You can\u8217't have more than +2 ranks in any given specialty. You can\u8217't assign more than eight ranks to the specialties corresponding to each attribute (Verge, Affinity, Guile).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add one language.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add one armor prowess or weapon prowess.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Increase one of your social ranks by 1, to a limit of Noble (D10)/Artisan (D8).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Add one style maneuver of your choice. Limits: You can have a maximum of six style maneuvers.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once you have assigned your customizations, you receive four rewards equal to your Competency Die, two rewards equal to your lowest rank, and two rewards equal to your highest social rank. You can spend those normally to buy your starting equipment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Example of Class-Free Character Creation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player decides she\u8217's going to create a character who is all about airships. She starts with the base character and then spends her 30 customizations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Skill Competency:} In addition to the automatic skill competency, she also chooses to be competent with Dueling (for mid-air swordfights!), Military (for mid-air gun fights! and airship tactics), Nature (so she\u8217'll be good at exploring), and Science (since airships are pretty advanced technology). This uses four of her customizations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialty Ranks:} The player picks Parry +1 (mid-air swordfights!), Dodge +1 (mid-air gun fights!), Aim +1 (also mid-air gun fights!), Strategy +2 (airship tactics), Explore +2 (navigating), Blackpowder +1 (firing cannons!), and Clockworks +2 (fixing a broken airship). She also chooses Scholarship +1 (mainly for geographic knowledge), Etiquette +1 (customs of far-off lands), Inspire +1 (officers should be inspiring, right?) and Perceive +1 (for looking through a spyglass). Adding up the totals for each attribute, she finds +6 ranks total for Verve (Parry, Explore twice, Blackpowder, Inspire, Perceive), +4 ranks total for Affinity (Aim, Etiquette, Clockworks twice), and +4 ranks for Guile (Dodge, Strategy twice, Scholarship). This is under the limit of eight ranks per attribute, so she\u8217's good there. This costs 14 of her customizations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Languages:} The player decides she will be from England, and thus her free language is English. She also gets a bonus language from her +1 rank in Scholarship, and she picks French. She decides to also learn Italian and German, and that uses up two more customizations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Armor or Weapon Prowess:} While she doesn\u8217't think she needs armor prowess, the player does want to know how to use Swords, Pistols, and Cannons. She spends three customizations on those.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Social Rank:} Figuring that airships are rather expensive to maintain, the player pushes her social ranks up to the maximum of Noble (D10)/Artisan (D8). This uses five of her customizations, and she\u8217's only got two left from the original 30.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Style Maneuvers:} Looking over the list of style maneuvers in Chapter 5, the player finds two that thinks will be most appropriate for a future air-captain like herself. She selects Powdersmith (when creating or repairing a device with a blackpowder flintlock power source, a phlogistone furnace power source, or an explosion component, spend 1 Style Point to add Blackpowder dice to a Clockworks roll) and Naval Hilt (when using a cutlass, spend 1 Style Point to add Explore dice to a Parry roll). This uses up her last two customizations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Starting Equipment:} Naturally, the player chooses to start with a corsair outfit, and for her free weapon chooses a cutlass. She receives rewards of 4D6 (from her Competency Die), 2D8 (her Artisan social rank) and 1D10 (her Noble social rank). It\u8217's not quite enough to buy an airship, so she instead buys a cutlass (1D6 cost), a mariner\u8217's astrolabe (1D6 cost), a spyglass (1D6 cost), repair tools (1D6 cost), a double pistol (1D8 cost) because it\u8217's cool, and a deck cannon (1D10 cost) since she always wanted a cannon. Doesn\u8217't everyone? This leaves her with a 1D8 reward, which she chooses to spend on four supplies of clockwork gears so she can repair an airship or make nifty toys.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Option: Creating a Custom Class\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If only one of the classes appeals to you, you can create a custom class with the Gamemaster\u8217's consent. (Having two custom classes is not recommended; choose one standard class in addition to your custom class.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Make the following choices and write them down:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Name and Description:} Decide what role the class will play in French or European. How is this class different from existing classes?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Suggested Classes and Passions:} Choose at least 3 suggested classes and passions that fit the class concept. {\b Limit:} You can\u8217't choose Duelist as one of the classes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Social Rank:} If the class is primarily focused on combat, then the Social Rank should be Soldier (D6). If the class requires formal education or apprenticeship, then the Social Rank should be Artisan (D8). Otherwise the class should probably be Commoner (D0). {\b Limit:} A custom class can\u8217't be Noble (D10) or Royal (D12) social rank.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties and Skill Competency:} Choose six different specialties that make sense for the class; these all gain +1. The Skill Competencies correspond to those specialties, with the exception of skills that everyone is already competent in using. {\b Limits:} Classes never give specialty ranks in Initiative. Each attribute (Verve, Affinity, Guile) can have at most 3 specialties associated with it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Weapon and Armor Prowess:} If the class would know how to use specific weapons or armor types, pick up to four of those, total. Remember that everyone already knows how to use a Knife.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bonus Gear:} Choose one outfit that the class will receive for free. If the class requires the use of one or more tools, pick one of those tools as well as 4 supplies of the appropriate type. If the class has weapon or armor prowess, choose up one weapon and one type of armor. Remember that everyone gets one common weapon for free.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Style Maneuvers: }Choose six style maneuvers from the list of style maneuvers that are appropriate for this class: two that allow a reroll of one skill, two that allow one die to be maximized on a specialty roll, and two that let you add dice from one pool to another under specific circumstances.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you\u8217've finished creating your class, let your Gamemaster review it to see if it fits her concept of the world and the campaign. She can provide suggestions on how you can modify the class if she sees potential problems with the class.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Gamemaster-Created Classes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Gamemasters, you can create classes too, and offer them as additional choices for your players. You should try to follow the general guidelines given for players, although you can customize the social rank, bonus gear, armor prowess, and weapon prowess. You shouldn\u8217't give a class specialty ranks in Initiative, and a class shouldn\u8217't have more than 8 style maneuvers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Skills and Specialties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are 12 skills, ranging from Culture to Streetwise. Each of these skills has three specialties, corresponding to the three Attributes of Verve, Affinity, and Guile.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Using Skills\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To use a skill, first you determine under which specialty the task you want to perform falls. Your dice pool starts with one die of that specialty\u8217's corresponding attribute; this is your Attribute Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you have competency in that skill, you can add your Competency Die to the dice pool. There are four skills that all player characters are competent at using: Defense, Initiative, Interaction, and Observation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can have +0, +1, +2, +3, +4, or +5 ranks in each specialty, although a starting character is initially limited to only +2 ranks. Each rank adds an additional die of the same size as your Attribute Die to the dice pool; these are your Specialty Dice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many specialties allow you to add an Item Die from a tool or item to the dice pool as well, as described under the separate listings for each specialty. Weapon Dice and Armor Dice are subcategories of Item Dice; you can only add a Weapon or Armor die if you have prowess with that weapon or armor. You can have only one Item Die in any given dice pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You might have a Bonus Die that you can include in your dice pool under certain circumstances. Tag Dice and Advantage Dice are subcategories of Bonus Dice. A Tag Die is temporary and is based on a word, a phrase, a person, a place, a thing, or a concept. Your Advantage Die is used in combat, and can progress from +1D6 up to +1D12. You can only have one Bonus Die in a dice pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Factors that make your skills harder to use assign a Drop Penalty to your dice pool. Such factors range from Wounds to language barriers. Each Drop Penalty specifies a number of dice that are dropped \u8211- meaning removed \u8211- from your dice pool before you roll. A Drop 2 penalty means you remove 2 dice. You can choose which dice to drop, and so you\u8217're going to want to drop the smallest size dice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once you\u8217've finished constructing your dice pool, you roll all the dice at once. You select the dice that resulted in the highest two numbers, and you discard the results of the other dice. Then you see what the Gamemaster rolls on the opposition dice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two types of opposition dice. Some are rolls of your opponent\u8217's corresponding specialty, such as her Defense (Parry) roll against your Dueling (Lunge) roll. In other situations you might be rolling against standard opposition, rolled by the Gamemaster. Standard opposition pools consist of three dice of the same size, from Easy (3D6) to Very Difficult (3D12).\par}
