{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Float a Proposal:} You propose a course of action, and create a +1D0 Tag Die based on that proposal. Until the end of the scene, you can use that Tag Die as a Bonus Die on appropriate rolls, including further Negotiate rolls \u8211- or Wealth rolls if you are haggling over a purchase. If you create a new proposal, the old Tag Die ends.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Refine the Offer:} For every two success points you spend, the Tag Die of your existing proposal increases by one die size.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Counter-Offer:} If the other party has a Tag Die, you can decrease her die size by one step, or remove her Tag Die entirely if she has a +1D6 Bonus Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Put It In Writing:} You get the other party to agree to sign a written document after you close the deal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Reach Compromise:} You and the other party come to a compromise that benefits you both equally, more or less, and you close the deal. All Tag Dice created by either party immediately end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gain 1 Style Point:} You gain one Style Point; you must describe how you use the Specialty with style, and you can only have a maximum of three Style Points at any time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Close the Deal:} You end the negotiation. Whatever you and the other party have agreed upon is how it the terms will remain, and the other party won\u8217't renegotiate terms in this scene. If you are haggling over a purchase, you can use the Tag Die of your proposal as a Bonus Die on your wealth roll; if the other party has a Tag Die, she can add that to the opposition roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gain the Upper Hand:} You end the negotiation. You get what you were hoping to gain without major concessions. The other party loses Tag Dice she may have created during the negotiation.\par}
