{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Gamemaster\u8217's Toolbox: New Style Maneuvers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As the Gamemaster, you can create new Style Maneuvers that can be chosen by your players.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Reroll maneuvers} cost one Style Point and allow for one broad type of roll to be rerolled. For example, you could create a maneuver that allows a reroll on Wealth rolls, attack rolls with a rapier, or rolls that use one of the character\u8217's passions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Maximize maneuvers} cost two Style Points and allow one specific kind of die to be maximized. Any given pool can only have one maximized die. Examples of appropriate maneuvers include maximizing the Mount die of a mount or a specific weapon die, such as a pistol. Don\u8217't make the maneuver too specific; that\u8217's what conditional maneuvers are for.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Conditional maneuvers} cost one Style Point and let the character add dice from one specialty to another roll, but only under certain conditions. The conditions you choose should be fairly specific and not overly broad, but they should also be something that a determined player could use at least once per game session, if not more often.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Initiative maneuvers} don\u8217't exist, period. There aren\u8217't any Charms or Style Maneuvers that add to Initiative rolls. You probably shouldn\u8217't invent any, either; that limitation is there for a reason. You can, however, create conditional maneuvers that add Initiative specialties to other dice rolls.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Finally, you need to decide which classes, nationalities, or other groups have access to the new maneuver. Perhaps it\u8217's a lost sword technique only taught to students of a retired blademaster, or it\u8217's commonly practiced by adult members of a house of the Ifran desert. It\u8217's possible you might decide that no groups can freely choose your new maneuver, in which case players will need to pay the additional XP cost when choosing it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Players, you don\u8217't have the option to create your own Style Maneuvers whenever you want \u8211- but you can always suggest one to your Gamemaster and maybe she\u8217'll like the idea!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Equipment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In this chapter, we\u8217'll look at the mundane clothes, weapons, tools, and other items that a cavalier might use during the course of her day.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Item Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Every item has a scale that describes the general size of the item: pocket scale, handheld scale, portable scale, human scale, furniture scale, room scale, and building scale. In general, it\u8217's easy enough to determine the scale of most items, but for some items a scale is explicitly listed in the lists that follow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The scale concept is used in the optional rules for Encumbrance, later in this chapter, as well as for clockwork devices in Chapter 9, \u8220"Specialty Equipment,\u8221" and animals in Chapter 20, \u8220"Opponents.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Pocket Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A pocket-scale device is light, easily concealed, requires only one hand to operate, and can be carried within a pocket or beneath clothing without attracting undue notice. Examples include small pistols or knives, flasks of alchemical brews, and a pet mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Weapons of this size are classified as Either Hand weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Handheld Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A handheld item usually requires one hand to operate and can be carried on a belt, in a holster, or in a scabbard. Most can\u8217't be easily concealed unless you\u8217're willing to forego easy access. Examples include most swords, tool kits, bucklers, and large hats.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When describing animals, such as cats or small dogs, handheld scale is known as pet scale. Weapons of this size are classified as Main Hand weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Portable Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A portable-scale item is one which requires two hands to carry and operate, or perhaps can be carried as a backpack. Examples include two-handed swords, muskets, and bar stools.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The equivalent scale for animals is companion scale. A portable-scale weapon is classified a Both Hands weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Human Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An object roughly the size of a person \u8211- such as a statue or a suit of rigid armor \u8211- can\u8217't be easily carried by a single person without requiring her full attention. Other examples include work carts, heavy chairs, and velocipedes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Furniture Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Larger than a human but smaller than a room, a carriage-scale item is around the size of a bed, a wardrobe dresser, or a small carriage. At best, an adult human can drag a furniture-scale item around but can\u8217't pick it up. Other furniture-scale items are horses, rowboats, and thrones.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In descriptions of animals, furniture scale is known as mount scale.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Room Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Room-scale items can be rooms themselves, the amount of furnishings it takes to fill up a room, or an object of comparable size. In combat, each room-scale item is usually its own Area.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Mammoth scale is the equivalent of room scale when describing animals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Building Scale\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Building-scale items include buildings, of course, but also large vehicles such as sailing ships or airships. In combat situations, a building-scale object is usually divided into multiple Areas.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When talking about animals this large, such as giant squids or great whales, the term behemoth scale is used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ::::::::::::::::::::::::: option ::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::; #### Optional Rule: Encumbrance\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is an optional rule that the MJ can use if it will enhance her game. In most cases, the calculations are more effort than they\u8217're worth and rarely provide any actual change in the game. However, if the players start carrying around dozens of heavy items, the MJ might decide that this use can help bring her players\u8217' gear into line with her expectations for the game. {\i The Queen\u8217's Cavaliers} is a swashbuckling action game, and not about lugging around heavy weights!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Carrying Limit\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A human carrying a Person-sized object takes a Drop 2 penalty on attack rolls (Dueling, Brawl, and Aim), and cannot move more than one area in a given turn. Humans cannot usually move items of Carriage size or higher, unless it\u8217's got wheels or something similar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You pick up an unconscious colleague and carry her over your shoulders. That\u8217's obviously a Person-sized object, so you get a Drop 2 penalty and can\u8217't run.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Combining Encumbrance\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Three items of a smaller size are equivalent to one item of larger size. So three Portable items are as bulky and heavy as one Person-sized object \u8211- meaning if you\u8217're carrying a musket, a zweihander, and a pike (all Portable-sized objects), you\u8217've got the equivalent of a Person-sized object and take the Drop 2 penalty, plus you can\u8217't run.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Three Pocket-sized items equal a Handheld object; three Handheld-sized items equal a Portable object; and three Portable-sized items equal a Person-sized object. You could carry eight Handheld objects \u8211- say, a cutlass, a buckler, and a brace of six pistols tied together by rope \u8211- and not be slowed down, because that only equals two Portable items, which is less than a Person-sized object.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Worn Items\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Items that are specifically designed to be worn \u8211- and which can\u8217't be removed easily during the middle of a fight (and sometimes, even after a fight) \u8211- count as one size lower for purposes of encumbrance when worn. A suit of armor is normally Person-sized, but if you\u8217're wearing it, it counts as Portable-sized. (If you\u8217're trying to carry an empty suit of armor, though, it counts as Person-sized.) A worn breastplate (Portable) counts as a Handheld item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Pocket-sized items which are worn don\u8217't count at all for encumbrance purposes, unless you\u8217're wearing three of the same kind \u8211- for example, a worn wrist holster (Pocket) or two doesn\u8217't weigh you down at all. Three worn wrist holsters, however, would equal a Pocket-sized objects \u8211- base size of Pocket, stepped up to Handheld for three of them, then stepped down again to Pocket size for being worn.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Clothing of any type never counts for calculating encumbrance \u8211- it\u8217's all considered Pocket size (regardless of actual size) and thus is not included when worn unless you\u8217're doing something silly like wearing three different capes at the same time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Other Things That Don\u8217't Weigh Very Much\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Medicine, alchemy supplies, draughts and unguents, poisons, and other small consumables don\u8217't count for encumbrance unless you\u8217've got 9 of them, in which case they count as a Pocket-sized object. Ammunition and powder for your guns, arrows for your crossbows and bows, and other types of ammo don\u8217't ever count; they\u8217're included with the weapon itself (especially as they\u8217're not tracked in {\i The Queen\u8217's Cavaliers}).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Other supplies (art supplies, blackpowder supplies, clockwork gears, fabric, foodstuffs) count as one Pocket-size object for every three units you carry. So if you\u8217're carrying, say, 10 units of clockwork gears, that counts as three Pocket-size objects, or 1 Handheld object. Two or fewer units of these supplies don\u8217't count for encumbrance purposes.\par}
