{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Availability\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are no set values for availability, but as a general rule the highest die in an item\u8217's cost is often equal to its availability rating, or the level of skill required to create the item, whichever is higher.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Gamemaster can change the availability based on the geographic location; for example, if you are in Paris, it\u8217's Very Common to find a sword, while in the Provinces it might be Very Common to buy a draft horse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The dice pool opposing a Wealth roll is equal to the cost plus the availability. Buying a sword in Paris would be D6 (cost) plus D0 (availability), or 1D6. Buying an Airship in Paris is 4D12 (cost) plus 1D12 (availability), or 5D12, since airships are very rarely available for purchase.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Making a Wealth Roll\par}
