{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Purchase Item:} You can purchase the item or service in question. If the item has \u8220"bulk\u8221" beside the cost, it can be purchased in bulk, and each success point you spend gives you one more of the item; otherwise, you can only purchase the item or service once.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b No Drop:} You don\u8217't drop a die from your Wealth pool because of this roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Dropped Dice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Dropped dice are restored at the start of the next game session. You can (and probably should) drop a D0 die if it is in your Wealth pool; it\u8217's always best to drop your lowest die rather your highest die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you get enough success points on your Wealth roll, you don\u8217't have to drop any dice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can\u8217't choose to drop Barter or Reward dice when you make a Wealth roll, as they are not a permanent part of your Wealth pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Buying in Bulk\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Certain items in the equipment list can be purchased in bulk; these are marked by the word \u8220"bulk\u8221" after the cost. For those items, and only those items, you can buy multiple quantities by expending additional success points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are spending a Reward, you get a quantity of items equal to half your Reward die size when buying items in bulk. For example, if you spend a D8 reward on fabric (cost D6), you get 4 pieces of fabric.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Charmwoven Items\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You purchase a Charmwoven item in the same way that you purchase anything else \u8211- but the cost is equal to the base cost of the item plus the Charm die. This is in addition to the availability, which in most cases is equal to the Charm die as well.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, if you wish to purchase a cavalier hat with a D8 Charm for Dueling (Riposte), the cost will be D6 for the hat, D8 for the Charm, and D8 for finding an Expert charmweaver, for a total of 2D8+1D6 as the opposition to your Wealth roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By comparison, an uncharmed cavalier hat would cost D6 plus D0 availability in Lutetia (they\u8217're all the rage these days), for a total of 1D6.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Cost D0\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An item with a cost of D0 is not free; it still requires a successful Wealth roll to purchase and thus a die dropped (or a D0 or higher Reward to purchase without rolling).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Likewise, a D0 Reward actually is something, but it doesn\u8217't do much except let you purchase a single D0 item (such as a knife).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A D0 Barter die has no value, however, so you don\u8217't need to bother with those.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Barter Dice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you sell items, you gain Barter dice equal to the cost (not the availability) of the item. Barter dice are recorded on the character sheet below the Wealth pool, and can be included in a Wealth roll whenever you wish. However, after being successfully used once, Barter dice are expended.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can include as many Barter dice as you have in any given roll, or you can save them as long as you wish.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a failed Wealth roll, any Barter dice used are not expended, and can be used again in the future.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, if you want to sell your riding horse (cost D8), you gain a D8 Barter die. If you then turn around and buy a warhorse, you can choose to add the D8 to your Wealth roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Rewards\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Reward is a more tangible, less abstract quantity of Wealth, usually bequeathed by a non-player character. Such Rewards could include a grant from the Queen, a bounty for capturing a wanted criminal, or a prize for winning a tournament.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each Reward has a die value associated with it, from D0 to D12. You can use a Reward to automatically purchase, without making a Wealth roll, any item or service which is equal to or less than the Reward\u8217's die value.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 New characters begin the game with three Rewards, equal in value to the dice in their Wealth pool. Additional Rewards should be granted by the Gamemaster. A typical good deed may net a Reward equal to the player characters\u8217' Competency die, while capturing a fugitive could earn a Reward equaling the criminal\u8217's Competency die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Weapons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In game terms, there are three broad categories that weapons fall into: dueling, aimed, and explosive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dueling Weapon:} A weapon that can be used in close-quarters combat with one or more of the Dueling (Lunge), Dueling (Riposte), Dueling (Feint), or Defense (Parry) specialties. Examples are swords, knives, quarterstaves, and pikes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Aimed Weapon:} A weapon that can be used at range with the Military (Aim) specialty. These include crossbows, muskets, pistols, and some thrown weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Explosive Weapon:} Unlike some aimed weapons which also use blackpowder, such as flintlock pistols or muskets, aiming an explosive weapon isn\u8217't the problem. It\u8217's preventing yourself from blowing up in the process. To make an attack with explosives, you use the Science (Blackpowder) specialty. This category includes cannons, grenades, and bombs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Free Starting Weapon\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you create your character, you get a free weapon in addition to any granted by your classes and any additional weapons you might also buy. If you don\u8217't want a free weapon, you can instead take a +1D6 Barter die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can pick from the following basic weapons:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cutlass} (Sword +1D8, Main Hand)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Dagger} (Knife +1D6, Either Hand)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Flintlock Pistol} (Pistol +1D6, Either Hand)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Rapier} (Sword +1D8, Main Hand)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sabre} (Sword +1D6, Main Hand, Cavalry)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Smallsword} (Sword +1D6, Either Hand)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Weapon Qualities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are four qualities possessed by all weapons: the type of Weapon Prowess needed to use it, the Weapon Die that can be added as an Item Die to your dice pools, the number of Hands you need to use to attack effectively with one, and the Specialties with which that weapon can be used. Some weapons also possess Success Table Additions which give you additional ways to spend success points when making certain kinds of rolls with the weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Weapon Prowess:} Weapon Prowess is your knowledge of the basics of how to attack and defend with that weapon. There are nine types of Weapon Prowess: bow, cudgel, knife, musket, net, pistol, polearm, sword, and whip. All player characters automatically have Knife Prowess.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Weapon Die:} You can add the Weapon Die to a Dice Pool as an Item Die if you have the appropriate prowess for the weapon. If you lack prowess in a weapon, you can still use the weapon \u8211- you just don\u8217't get to add the Weapon Die to your pool.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hands:} Some weapons can be used freely in either hand, others require two hands to use, and some are just intended for main-hand use. These are represented by the following weapon qualities:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Main Hand:} This weapon can be used in one hand. You can have another weapon in your other hand, but it must be usable in Either Hand.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Either Hand:} This weapon also requires only one hand to use, but unlike a Main Hand weapon, you can wield one in each hand (known as \u8220"dual wielding\u8221") or as a secondary weapon with a Main Hand weapon in your primary hand.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Both Hands:} You need both hands to use this weapon.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Scale:} The scale of a weapon depends on the number of hands required to use it. Unless stated otherwise, Main Hand weapons are considered handheld scale, Either Hand weapons are pocket scale, and Both Hand weapons are portable scale.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Specialties:} These qualities list the specific specialties that can be used with that weapon. If a specialty isn\u8217't listed, it\u8217's up to the Gamemaster whether it\u8217's possible to use the weapon that way, and what kind of Drop penalty you\u8217'll receive; for example, using Parry with a musket or Aim with a rapier could have pretty heavy penalties \u8211- Drop 2 for the musket, Drop 4 for the rapier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Aim:} Any attack with handheld weapons made at range uses the Aim specialty, from throwing a knife to firing a musket. If you have prowess in the weapon you\u8217're using, you can add its Weapon Die to your Aim roll as an Item Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Block:} Defense (Block) allows the use of armor and general toughness to throw off the effects of an attack. It can be used to negate attacks from either Dueling or Aimed weapons. You add your armor\u8217's Armor Die to your Block roll as an Item Die if you have Armor Prowess in that item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Brawl:} Only a few Dueling weapons can be used as part of a Military (Brawl) attack or defense; Brawl usually doesn\u8217't use an Item Die of any kind. Brawl can be used to inflict Yield, to disarm or knock down an opponent, or to defend against a Brawl attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Feint:} The primary use of Dueling (Feint) is to build Advantage during a fight through tricky maneuvering or a false attack to draw the your opponent off-guard. It can also inflict Yield or trigger a Riposte. If you have prowess in the weapon you\u8217're using, you can add its Weapon Die to your Riposte roll as an Item Die, although you can perform a Feint without a weapon also.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Lunge:} A Lunge is a straightforward attack against an opponent using a Dueling weapon, usually by stabbing, chopping, slashing, or bashing. It\u8217's the best way to inflict either Yield or Wounds on your target. If you have prowess in the weapon you\u8217're using, add its Weapon Die to your Lunge roll as an Item Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Parry:} This specialty of the Defense skill can be used to negate incoming attacks from Dueling weapons, and if possible, trigger a Riposte. You need to have a weapon, improvised or otherwise, in your hand to attempt a Parry. If you have prowess in that weapon, add its Weapon Die to your Parry roll as an Item Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Riposte:} Dueling (Riposte) is a triggered Dueling attack that you can use by spending success points from another specialty \u8211- either Defense (Parry) or Dueling (Feint). A successful Riposte can inflict Yield or Wounds, or decrease your opponent\u8217's Advantage. The Defense (Parry) specialty cannot be used to defend against a Riposte. If you have prowess in the weapon you\u8217're using, you can add its Weapon Die to your Riposte roll as an Item Die.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Success Table Additions:} Some weapons have additions to the success tables for specific specialties, such as Knockdown or additional damage. These are represented by the + notation for success points, such as Lunge (+++: Unhorse).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Dueling Weapons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Dueling weapons are, by definition, weapons that can be used with the Dueling skill and its specialties \u8211- Lunge, Riposte, Feint, and Defense (Parry). Not all weapons can be used with all specialties, however.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dueling Weapon Prowess:} The types of Weapon Prowess used with dueling weapons are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cudgel Prowess:} Any Dueling weapon used to bludgeon someone is a cudgel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Knife Prowess:} In addition to serving as Dueling weapons, you can also throw some knives with the Aim specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Net Prowess:} A net can be used as a Dueling weapon, although this can be rare.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Polearm Prowess:} A polearm is any long-hafted Dueling weapon, typically (but not always) with the Reach quality.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sword Prowess:} A Dueling weapon with a blade and a hilt. The pointy end goes in the other guy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Whip Prowess:} Whips are usually used in one hand, and most have Reach.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dueling Weapon Qualities:} In addition to the qualities common to all weapons, dueling weapons could have two additional qualities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cavalry:} A dueling weapon with the Cavalry quality must be used with your Main Hand. If you are using this weapon while riding a mount, you can substitute the mount\u8217's Item Die for your Weapon Die against an unmounted opponent.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Reach:} A dueling weapon with Reach can be used to attack into an adjacent area as well as your own.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Success Table Additions for Dueling Weapons:} Some dueling weapons have additions to the success tables for specific specialties, such as Knockdown or additional damage. These are represented by the + notation for success points after the specialty name, such as Lunge (+++: Unhorse). On a success with a weapon possessing that quality, you could spend 3 success points to knock your target off her horse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Break Weapon:} You snap your target\u8217's blade or hilt. You can only do this if your target attempts to Parry your attack and fails, or if you are performing a Parry yourself. A broken weapon is useless except as an improvised weapon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Disarm:} You can disarm your opponent of the weapon she is using to attack you or the weapon she\u8217's using to Parry your attack. (This can\u8217't be used when defending against a Brawl attack.) You get to choose if the weapon ends up on the ground in your Area, in an adjacent Area, or in your hand if you have one free.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Execute a Riposte:} You can make a Riposte attack. This is the only way to use the Riposte specialty; it has to follow a successful use of a Specialty or weapon with this effect on its Success Table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Grab:} You can snag an item worn by your target as long as you can see it, the item is Handheld size or smaller, and it\u8217's not being held by your opponent. You get to choose if the item ends up on the ground in your Area, or in your hand if you have one free.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Inflict 1 Wound:} Your opponent takes one Wound. If she takes more Wounds than her Wound Limit, she falls unconscious and is dying. Weapons with this quality allow you to inflict Wounds for a lower cost than usual.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Inflict 2 Wounds:} Your opponent takes two Wounds. If she takes more Wounds than her Wound Limit, she falls unconscious and is dying. Weapons with this quality allow you to inflict Wounds for a lower cost than usual.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Knockdown:} Your target is knocked prone, either in your Area or in an adjacent Area. Knocking an opponent into an adjacent Area can result in them falling or otherwise taking environmental damage. Prone characters suffer a Drop 1 penalty on attack and defense rolls, and cannot Move until they stand up; standing up is a Drop 1 combined action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Restrain:} You successfully catch your opponent with your weapon, holding them in place. A combatant who is held suffers a Drop 1 penalty on attack and defense rolls; for every two additional Success Points you spend, you can increase the Drop penalty by 1, to a maximum of Drop 4. Your opponent can escape by making a simple check against Standard Opposition, usually using Brawl or a weapon attack. On a success, your opponent can break your weapon, let it fall in their Area, or grab it themselves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Unhorse:} If your target is riding a mount, they fall off that mount and end up prone. Unhorsing an opponent can result in them falling or otherwise taking environmental damage. In addition, your mount can make a trample attack right now for free, if it has that quality. Prone characters suffer a Drop 1 penalty on attack and defense rolls, and cannot Move until they stand up. Standing up is a Drop 1 combined action, and remounting is an additional Drop 3 penalty.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Availability of Dueling Weapons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To purchase any item you must roll against a pool consisting of that item\u8217's availability and its cost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Common dueling weapons are those which aren\u8217't hard at all to find any settlement of decent size, and even in some smaller towns. Those are listed in the following tables.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The availability of common weapons is almost always 1D0 in settlements of any size. The exceptions are cutlass, rapier, sabre, and smallsword \u8211- the common swords \u8211- in a small rural settlement. In such situations, the availability increases to 1D6.\par}
