{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Aimed Weapons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Arbalest:} Also known as a heavy crossbow, the arbalest is harder to use than a common crossbow but packs a larger punch.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Arquebus:} A smaller and lighter musket with shorter range and less firepower.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Blunderbuss:} The flared barrel of this musket makes it easier to reload, but also reduces its effective range.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Caliver:} Another type of musket that can reload faster without the reduced range of the blunderbuss, but with a smaller Weapon Die.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Composite Bow:} A heavier bow with longer effective range and pull.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Crossbow:} The crossbow uses stored mechanical power to fire bolts, instead of relying upon personal muscle power as a normal bow does.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Double Musket:} The primary advantage of this double-barreled musket is the ability to fire twice, once per barrel, without reloading. If you choose to fire both barrels in the same shot, the Weapon Die increases to 1D12, but you take a Drop 1 penalty because it\u8217's harder to aim. You can reload just one barrel of a double musket with a Drop 3 action.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Double Pistol:} Like the double musket, the double pistol allows one shot per barrel without having to reload. If you choose to fire both barrels in the same shot, the Weapon Die increases to 1D8, but you take a Drop 1 penalty because it\u8217's harder to aim. You can reload just one barrel of a double pistol with a Drop 2 action.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Dragon:} This heavier version of a pistol is favored by cavalry \u8211- especially Dragoons, who take their name from the use of this large pistol.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Flintlock Musket:} This is a standard musket used by infantry throughout Europe.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Flintlock Pistol:} A single-barrel pistol found all over Europe.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Hunting Bow:} This standard bow, also called a shortbow or flatbow, has been used for millennia in pretty much every nation.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Rifled Musket:} With a rifled barrel to provide better accuracy at long range, this musket is the favored weapon of snipers.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Thrown Dagger:} A dagger doesn\u8217't have be reloaded, but you take a Drop 1 penalty to draw it as you would with any other weapon \u8211- and once it\u8217's thrown, you don\u8217't have it any more.\line \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Thrown Spear:} Like a dagger, a thrown spear must be drawn first but doesn\u8217't require ammunition.\line \sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Ammunition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Firing a musket or pistol uses a small amount of blackpowder and a bullet, while a bow requires an arrow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, strict tracking of ammunition and powder doesn\u8217't contribute to the swashbuckling adventure style of the genre. If you have an Aimed weapon that has a Reload value, you\u8217're assumed to have enough powder, bullets, or arrows to fire your weapon and reload it as many times as necessary.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This applies even if you use someone else\u8217's weapon, or a weapon you just picked up \u8211- you just don\u8217't track ammo for Aimed weapons. Except, of course, for explosive weapons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Explosive Weapons\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike conventional weapons, which use Dueling or Military (Aim) rolls for attack, explosive weapons affect an entire area and inflict damage on every creature, object, or other target within that area.\par}
