{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each device consists of the following:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 Casing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 or more Power Sources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1 or more Components\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Gear Space:} Each casing has a certain amount of gear space available, depending upon its size. The power source and the components use up that space once installed. A miniaturization component can be installed in a casing to increase its effective gear space.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power:} Each power source delivers a set amount of power, dependent on the type of power source and the method of producing that power. Each component consumes a specified amount of power, and the power source\u8217's output must be enough to cover the power used by the components. Power is measured in power units.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Complexity:} The complexity of a device is equal to the number of power sources plus the number of components.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Constructing a Device\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Note: These rules are obsolute and this section needs to be rewritten to reflect the current crafting rules.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are five steps to creating a device:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Plan the Device\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Purchase the Supplies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Build the Parts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Install the Parts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Complete the Device\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Plan the Device\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Before you start, you should plan out what you want your device to do. Decide how large the device will be \u8211- the size of its casing. Determine what capabilities it will have by the components you choose to install, and make sure that you have a strong enough power source to provide power to those components.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once you have the device planned out, you can spend four hours to make a Science (Calculus) roll to draft a set of plans for building the device. This is optional, but is highly recommended as it gives you an additional die to roll when installing parts in your device and completing it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The difficulty of the Science (Calculus) roll to draw plans is determined by the complexity of the device you are designing, as shown on the table below.\par}
