{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Maximum Die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Prototype:} If you have an existing prototype for the device, either created by yourself or by someone else, you gain a bonus D6 die on the roll to draw plans. The prototype does not need to be currently functional for you to gain this bonus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Purchase the Supplies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are three ways to acquire the parts needed for constructing a device: build them yourself, buy them from another clockworker, or salvage the parts from another device.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are going to build your own parts, you will need to buy gear supplies. Make a Wealth roll against the cost and availability of gear supplies \u8211- D8 for the cost, and D6 availability unless you are in a large city (in which case the availability is D0). Each success point on the Wealth roll enables you to buy one unit of gear supplies since they are a bulk item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are going to buy certain parts, you will also make a Wealth roll based on the cost of the part (casing, power source, or component) that you wish to purchase. The cost for each is listed in the descriptions of each part later in this chapter. A casing has an availability of D0, while power sources and components have an availability equal to the highest die of their costs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For details on salvaging parts and supplies, see the later section on Salvage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Build the Parts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can save money by building your own casing, although this does consume more time. A roll is not necessary, although you must have competency in the Science (Clockworks) specialty to construct a usable casing. See the later section on Constructing a Power Source for more information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Building a power source or a component requires a number of gear supplies as shown on the table for that part, and at least four hours\u8217' work. At the end of that time, make a Science (Clockworks) roll and for each success point, the clockworker can spend 1 Creation Point\u8217's worth of gear supplies to create components or power sources. Multiple rolls may be required to create all the parts needed for a complex device.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Skill Limit:} The total number of gears that you can spend on a single part is limited to your number of specialty ranks in Science (Clockworks).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Standard Opposition:} The difficulty for this roll is Easy (3D6) if you are in a workshop, or Hard (3D10) if you are not.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tools:}If you have clockworker\u8217's tools, you gain an item die (usually D6) on this roll. If you are in a workshop, you gain a D8 item bonus instead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Plans:} The plans for the overall device do not apply on this roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Prototype:} You gain no bonus for having a prototype of the device when making this roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Install the Parts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Installing a power source or component in a casing requires a Science (Clockworks) roll (or series of rolls). The difficulty is Easy (3D6) if you are in a workshop, or Hard (3D10) if you are not. Each roll takes four hours, and each success point installs one power source or component.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tools:} If you have clockworker\u8217's tools, you gain an item die (usually D6) on this roll. If you are in a workshop, you gain a D8 item bonus instead.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Plans:} If you have plans for the device, you gain a bonus die based on the quality of the plans when making this roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Prototype:} If you have a prototype of the device, you gain a bonus D6 die on this roll. The prototype does not need to be currently functional for you to gain this bonus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Complete the Device\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once all the components have been successfully installed, the device needs to be completed. This requires no roll, but does require one hour of work per point of complexity of the device.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Casings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Casings are measured by their physical size, which determines the amount of gear space within the casing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Purchasing a Casing:} Casings are either purchased at the cost shown below or constructed by the clockworker for no cost. The availability of a casing is always D0. Gear supplies cannot be spent on casing costs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Creating a Casing:} It takes one hour per point of Gear Space to create a casing. No skill roll is required, but the clockworker must have at least one rank in the Clockworks specialty.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Casing Notation:} A casing is described by listing the size of the casing followed by the gear space of that casing in parentheses. Examples: pocket (space 1), person (space 8), building (space 64).\par}
