{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Casings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Pocket Size\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A pocket-sized device is easily concealed, requires only one hand to operate, and can be carried within a pocket or beneath clothing. Examples include pocketwatches and wrist holsters.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Handheld Size\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A handheld device requires usually requires one hand to operate and can be carried on a belt, in a holster, or in a scabbard. Examples include clockwork pistols and gearswords.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Portable Size\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A portable device is one which requires two hands to carry and operate, or perhaps can be carried as a backpack. Most don\u8217't need to be self-mobile. Examples include clockwork muskets and wing-gliders.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Person Size\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An object roughly the size of a person \u8211- such as a statue \u8211- can\u8217't be easily carried by a single person without requiring her full attention. Most are therefore either stationary devices or self-mobile. Examples include humanoid automata and velocipedes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Carriage Size\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Larger than a human but smaller than a room, carriage-sized devices are on the scale of large pieces of furniture. Unless self-mobile, they require several people in order to transport. Examples include clockwork carriages and some industrial machines.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Room Size\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Room-sized devices take up the entire space of a sizable room, and are therefore rarely portable unless self-mobile. Examples include some analytical engines and most watermills.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Building Size\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Devices the size of a building are usually as large as a two or three story building with a half-dozen rooms. Examples include airships and clock towers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Power Sources\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Power sources are rated by how much space they take up inside a casing, by how much power they can provide, and by how that power is activated to enable components.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Purchasing a Power Source:} A power source can be purchased, pre-assembled, for the cost shown on the table for that power source. The availability is equal to the highest cost die of the power source.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Constructing a Power Source:} Unless otherwise specified, a power source can be constructed by a clockworker. This requires a number of gear supplies as shown on the table for that power source, and at least four hours\u8217' work. At the end of that time, make a Science (Clockworks) roll and for each success point, the clockworker can spend 1 Creation Point\u8217's worth of gear supplies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Skill Limit:} The total number of gears that a clockworker can spend on a single power source is limited to her number of specialty ranks in Science (Clockworks). For example, a clockworker with Science (Clockworks) +3 can only spend 3 gears on creating a mainspring power source.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Note:} There are a few power sources that cannot be constructed using the Clockworks specialty. This will be noted in the description of the power source along with information about the required skill for construction. The roll is otherwise treated like the Clockworks specialty roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Power Source Notation:} A power source is described by listing the name of the power source followed by the space, power supply, other qualities of the power source, and the duration. Examples: gear train (space 1, power supply 2, Drop 1, one action); mainspring (space 4, power supply 4, wind 1 minute, duration 10 minutes); tension trigger (space 1, power supply 2, reset Drop 2, one use).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Alchemical Capacitor\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An alchemical capacitor is a simple jar device that is used to generate, capture, and store electrical energy through alchemical means. A crude electromechanical interface allows the energy of the capacitor to be released and used over an extended period of time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each alchemical capacitor functions for 24 hours before needing to be replaced and reinstalled in a device. The power supply\u8217's duration is the same if it is used once during that time period or used repeatedly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Creating an Alchemical Capacitor:} The Magicks (Brew) specialty is required to create an alchemical capacitor, and it requires the use of alchemical supplies to do so. The maximum number of alchemical supplies that can be spent to create an alchemical capacitor is equal to the brewer\u8217's ranks in Magicks (Brew).\par}
