{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Components\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Components provide the basic functionality of a clockwork device, and are rated by how much space they take up inside a casing, by how much power require to run, and by the effects the component can produce.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Purchasing a Component:} A component can be purchased, pre-assembled, for the cost shown on the table for that component type. The availability is equal to the highest cost die of the component.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Constructing a Component:} Unless otherwise specified, a component can be constructed by a clockworker. This requires a number of gear supplies as shown on the table for that component, and at least four hours\u8217' work. At the end of that time, make a Science (Clockworks) roll and for each success point, the clockworker can spend 1 Creation Point\u8217's worth of gear supplies to construct components or power sources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Skill Limit:} The total number of gears that a clockworker can spend on a component is limited to her number of specialty ranks in Science (Clockworks). For example, a clockworker with +3 Science (Clockworks) can only spend 3 gears on creating a movement component.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Component Notation:} A power source is described by listing the name of the power source followed by the space, power requirements, and other qualities of the component. Examples: articulation (space 1, power 0, Drop 1); carry (space 2, power 1, person); projectile weapon (space 3, power 1, weapon die d8, close Drop 0, short Drop 0, medium Drop 0, long Drop 2).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Armor\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Armor plating protects both the device itself and anyone using or within the device. The armor component grants an Armor Die that can be used for Defense (Block) rolls.\par}
