{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Clothing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Charmweaving, is the practice of adding specific dyes, trinkets, threads, and other magickal enhancements to articles of clothing. These enhancements provide bonuses to specific tasks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Clothing Qualities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Articles of clothing have the following qualities:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Worn On:} Each article of clothing is designed to be worn on a specific part of your body \u8211- head, shoulders, torso, hands, legs, or feet. In general, you can wear only one item per location, although you may be able to stack multiple cloaks on your shoulders under certain circumstances \u8211- check with your Gamemaster to be sure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Items worn on the legs can\u8217't have charms woven into them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Social Rank:} Some items are associated with certain social ranks. This doesn\u8217't restrict what you can wear, regardless of your own social rank, but it may affect how you and your outfit are seen by others. The social rank of an article of clothing can be used as an availability die in a purchase roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Scale:} Articles of clothing are usually handheld scale when carried, and don\u8217't contribute to encumbrance when worn if the optional system for encumbrance is used. Items wrapped up in a box for gifting or transport are one scale category higher, including the packaging.\par}
