{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Flourish to Gain Style\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Focus to Reroll Initiative\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Movement\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Prepare an Action\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Reload your Weapon\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use a Skill\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Minor actions are possible, such as drawing a weapon, mounting a horse, or opening a door. Most of those can simply be done as a combined action (see below), although you could also do that on your turn as your entire turn.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Combined Actions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many actions can be combined together with other actions. These actions don\u8217't require a dice roll, but instead impose a Drop Penalty on the primary action\u8217's roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, if you wish to draw your weapon, you could take an action to do that. Or you could combine drawing the weapon with making an attack with it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Draw a weapon\u8221" is a Drop 1 combined action. This means you\u8217'd take a Drop 1 penalty on whatever roll you choose to make that turn as your action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Drop Penalties for combined actions are cumulative; if you move to an adjacent area (another Drop 1 penalty) along with drawing your weapon, you now have a Drop 2 penalty on your attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A partial list of combined actions is shown below:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Drop 0:} Drop Weapon\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Drop 1:} Move, Stand Up, Dismount, Draw Weapon, Sheathe Weapon, Switch Hands, Imbibe Draught, Arm Grenade\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Drop 2:} Run, Retrieve Weapon, Improvise Weapon, Mount Horse, Reload (Pistol), Reload (Crossbow)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Drop 3:} Reload (Musket)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a desired combined action isn\u8217't listed, the Gamemaster can assign an appropriate Drop Penalty based on the examples listed above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can never combine two or more actions that require a dice roll, such as two attacks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you choose to not take an action that requires a dice roll, you can instead take multiple combined actions, up to a total of Drop 4. For example, reloading a pistol (Drop 2), dismounting (Drop 1), and moving (Drop 1). You wouldn\u8217't be able to also drink a draught in the same turn, because that would impose a Drop 5 penalty. (This limit only applies to Drop Penalties resulting from combined actions, and not from Wounds.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 List of Actions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The following actions require the use of your action during a turn, although some can be used as combined actions where noted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Attack\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character makes an attack against a target, using a Dueling skill (Lunge or Feint) or a Military Skill (Aim or Brawl). Your character must be within range of the target, or in the same Area for Dueling and Brawl attacks, although you could use a combined Move action to get closer to the target.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your character\u8217's target then gets to choose a specific Defense skill to use to react to the attack, and an opposed roll is made. The winner of the opposed roll gets to spend her Success Points as appropriate for the skill she used.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Assist\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can assist another character by taking an Assist action. This grants the other character bonus dice on their next roll equal to one of the following:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your character\u8217's Specialty dice, if she has ranks in the Specialty she is going to use.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Your character\u8217's Competency Die if she doesn\u8217't have ranks in the Specialty but is competent in that skill\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1D6\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A character can only receive the benefit from an Assist from two other characters. If the benefit is not used by the end of the current round, the benefit is lost.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b As a Combined Action:} You can\u8217't combine an Assist with other actions that require a dice roll, but you can use it with combined actions. Assist counts as a Drop 2 penalty when comparing against the maximum amount of Drop from combined actions (Drop 4).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You want to assist another player in attacking an opponent with Feint. Your character has 2 ranks in Feint, D8 for Guile, and a D8 Competency Die. You can give one of the following bonuses by assisting her:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 2D8 for the Feint specialty dice\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1D8 for the Competency Die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab 1D6 as a default\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Obviously in this case, you would choose the 2D8.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Flourish\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Flourish is an attempt to show off your character\u8217's talents in a way that is impressive \u8211- and which nets you Style Points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To execute a Flourish, choose one specialty and describe how your character is using it stylishly, as with gaining a Skill Point. Then make a skill roll against Easy (3D6) opposition. If you are successful, you can only spend your Success Points on gaining Style Points, up to a maximum (as always) of three.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You have no Style Points and make a Flourish based on your character\u8217's Dodge specialty. You roll a 14 with seven Success Points against an opposition roll of 9, succeeding in the roll. You can only spend your Success Points on gaining Style Points (at a cost of three Success Points each Style Point) and describe your character leaping onto a chair, a table, and then a barrel, looking quite dashing as she does.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Focus\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Focus is a re-centering of your character\u8217's attention, and allows you to reroll an Initiative roll with no opposition roll. You gain the following benefits from using Focus:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can change your character\u8217's position in the Initiative order to the new value you\u8217've rolled, or stay at your original position, whichever is better for you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can increase your current number of Initiative Points by the number that you rolled.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} At the start of the combat, you rolled a total of 5 with one Success Point on your Initiative roll. On the first turn, you decide to Focus and you get a better roll \u8211- a total of 11 with four Success Points (Initiative Points); you change your position in the Initiative order to 11, and add your one Initiative Point to the four you\u8217've just rolled, for a total five.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You later spend all five of those Initiative Points and in a subsequent turn, Focus again, getting a total of 9 with three Success Points; your position in the Initiative order doesn\u8217't change, but you do gain three more Initiative Points to spend.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Move or Run\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Movement allows you to change your position from one Area to another Area. A normal Move action takes you to an adjacent Area, while a Run action lets you move through to an Area two away from your starting position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b As a Combined Action:} A Move is a Drop 1 penalty, and a Run is a Drop 2 penalty. The most that you can Move in one turn is two Areas, so you can\u8217't do both a Run and a Move at the same time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Prepare\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can use a Prepare action to set up an action to occur after a specific event happens later in the round. You declare what action your character will take and what will trigger that action. (You can choose not to act when the trigger comes up, if circumstances have changed.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the end of the round comes and you have not taken the action because the trigger event hasn\u8217't happened, then you can either choose to take the action at the end of the turn, or forfeit your character\u8217's action for that turn.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you take any combined actions at the same time as your Prepare action, you apply the Drop Penalty when you take the prepared action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} Your character gets ready to rush into a room after a friend opens it, drawing her weapon (Drop 1) in the same turn that you declare your Prepare action. Your trigger is \u8220"when the door opens\u8221" and your character\u8217's action will be to move into the room (Drop 1) and attack someone there. This will have a total Drop 2 penalty due to the combined actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Later you prepare an attack with your sword to trigger \u8220"after my friend disarms our opponent.\u8221" This has no extra Drop penalty, since you aren\u8217't moving and your sword is already out. If your opponent doesn\u8217't become disarmed by the end of the round, you can either go ahead and make your attack, or wait until next round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Reload\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Reload action lets your character reload one of her firearms. (You don\u8217't have to reload a bow, but you do have to reload a crossbow.) Most weapons can be reloaded in one round, but it takes a total of 5 uses of Reload to reload a cannon.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b As a Combined Action:} Reloading a pistol or a crossbow is a Drop 2 penalty. Reloading a musket is a Drop 3 penalty. You can reload two pistols in one round, since that would be a Drop 4 penalty total, and Drop 4 is the limit of combined actions you can take in one round.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 Use a Skill\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a catch-all category for using a Specialty or Skill in a way which isn\u8217't an attack, either using the Specialty\u8217's own Success Tables or the generic table for Non-Combat Actions in Combat. (See the start of the Skills document in the playtest packet.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You decide to use the Deceive specialty to distract your character\u8217's opponent in a fight: \u8220"Hey, look, the cardinal\u8217's cavaliers are behind you!\u8221" Normally, Deceive takes one minute to use and doesn\u8217't have a direct combat application, so instead you use the Success Table for Non-Combat Actions. With your Success Points, you buy increases in Advantage to represent your successful bluff.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Advantage\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Advantage is an abstraction of how well your character is doing in a fight, expressed as a die value from D6 to D12. Advantage represents a wide variety of in-fiction states, including your character\u8217's relative positioning in an Area, her general sense of how the fight is going, her superior stance to her opponent, and even whether or not she is feeling the rhythm of the fight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Increasing Advantage\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You begin every combat with no Advantage Die and can increase your Advantage by spending Success Points, depending upon the Success Table for an action you\u8217've completed. The first time you buy an increase in Advantage, your Advantage Die goes up to D6; then D8, D10, and D12 with subsequent (or simultaneous) expenditures of Success Points on increasing Advantage.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You decide you want your character to make a Feint attack against her opponent, and you succeed with three Success Points. It\u8217's the start of the fight, so you have no Advantage to begin with, but the Increase Advantage option on the Feint success table lets you spend one Success Point for each increase of Advantage. The first point gives you a D6 Advantage Die, then the following two increase that die size to D10, spending all three of your Success Points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Using Advantage\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can include your Advantage die on any attack or defense roll that you make during combat. Each time you use your Advantage Die, it steps down one size \u8211- from D10 to D8, for example, or from D6 to no Advantage Die.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} You make a Lunge attack and elect to include your Advantage Die, which currently stands at a D10. You add a D10 to your dice pool for the attack, and after resolving the Lunge roll, your Advantage Die drops to a D8.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Other Combat Modifiers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Drop penalties can be applied during a fight based on the fictional circumstances \u8211- for example, if you are on the pitching and rolling deck of a ship, the Gamemaster can impose a Drop 1 penalty on physical skill checks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If an area provides cover from attacks, that imposes a Drop 1 or Drop 2 penalty on attacks that fire into that area.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Damage\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two types of damage: {\b Yield}, which is non-lethal, and {\b Wounds}, which bring a character closer to death while imposing penalties on combat-related actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Yield\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Yield is an abstraction representing a character\u8217's energy, enthusiasm for battle, fatigue level, and will to fight.\par}
