{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Drop Penalty from Wounds\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Drop Penalties from Wounds are cumulative with Drop Penalties for combined actions, and apply to the following skills and specialties:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Defense (all Specialties)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Dueling (all Specialties)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Military (Brawl, Aim)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} Your character is stabbed by an opponent\u8217's Lunge attack and receives one Wound. You now get a Drop 1 penalty on all applicable actions, such as attacking or defending. Later in the fight, you are shot for two more Wounds, which increases your penalty to Drop 4 \u8211- one more Wound and you\u8217'll be Dying.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Dying and Death\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Dying character is unconscious for the rest of the combat and cannot take actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 At the end of the combat, any Dying non-player character dies unless the player characters make a successful attempt (using the Medicine skill) to save that NPC \u8211- although the Gamemaster can rule that certain NPCs are beyond saving due to the extent of their injuries.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a player character is Dying at combat\u8217's end, that character\u8217's player can decide to have the character expire \u8211- possibly after awakening long enough to speak some last words to a companion \u8211- or receive treatment through the Medicine skill to keep that character alive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the Medicine skill is unsuccessful or the wounds are untreated, the player can make a Survival Roll using her character\u8217's Verve plus her Competency Die against Moderate Opposition (3D8).\par}
