{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Survive for 8 Hours:} The dying character doesn\u8217't die of her wounds for another eight hours per Success Point spent. Make another Survival Roll at the end of that time period.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Regain Consciousness:} The dying character is awake and can speak and react to the world around her, but can\u8217't take any actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Heal 1 Wound:} The dying character heals one wound and is no longer dying.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On a failed Survival Roll, the character dies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Example:} Your character receives a fourth Wound, taking her out of the fight. At the end of the fight, you can decide if she dies of her injuries, or fights to survive. If you choose the latter, and there\u8217's no medical aid nearby, you\u8217'll need to make a Survival Roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Healing Wounds\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike Yield, Wounds don\u8217't simply go away at the end of a combat. There are two ways to heal Wounds: the Medicine skill, and bed rest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Resting for two days will heal one Wound. Six days\u8217' bed rest is enough to fully heal all Wounds.\par}
