{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Opponents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Types of Opponents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are several types of opponents that can present challenges, both in combat and out of combat, for player characters. These opponents are rated in terms of how important they are to the story: rabble are at best extras, while minor opponents take supporting roles. Major opponents, of course, can challenge a group of player characters as major villains or powerful allies!\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs16 For the MJ: Using Opponents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Don\u8217't assume that all opponents are there to fight! A corrupt noble, scheming artisan, angry soldier, or even hapless rabble could complicate the heroes\u8217' lives without even lifting a finger.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use opposed rolls, such as a duplicitous politician\u8217's Deception vs.\u160?a player\u8217's Negotation, to represent a duel of words \u8211- trying to to convince a court of one\u8217's guilt or innocence.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Don\u8217't make rolls against Standard Opposition for opponents, though \u8211- you shouldn\u8217't ever be rolling against yourself! Either find a way for the player to oppose the roll, or just decide via fiat whether the opponent succeeds or not.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, if an opponent is actually friendly and wishes to help the player characters, use the rule for assisting to have them grant additional dice to the players\u8217' rolls.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Rabble\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Usually appearing in groups, rabble are faceless opposition who don\u8217't present a major challenge to the player characters. Rabble have the following characteristics:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab D0 or D6 Competency die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wealth pool based on 1 Social Rank die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Yield Limit of 3\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wound Limit of 1 (after taking 1 wound, they are Dying)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Attributes of D6/D6/D6, D8/D8/D8, or D6/D8/D10\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Maximum of +1 Specialty Ranks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Two Passions (D8, D6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab No Style Maneuvers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Start with 0 Style Points, with a maximum of 1 Style Point\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Usually appear in groups (up to twice the number of PCs)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Stock Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A stock character is one that has a tangible role in the game but probably doesn\u8217't need a name; instead, they are identified by their profession or story role. Characteristics of stock characters include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Competency die usually D6 (D8 or higher for elite characters)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wealth pool based on 1 Social Rank die plus Competency die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Yield Limit equal to 3 plus half the maximum value of their Competency die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wound Limit of 2 (Drop 1, Dying)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Attributes of D8/D8/D8 or D6/D8/D10\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Maximum of +2 Specialty Ranks in three Specialties (or higher for elite characters)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Three Passions (D10, D8, D6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One or Two Style Maneuvers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Start with 0 Style Points, with a maximum of 1 Style Point\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sometimes appear in groups (one per PC), or sometimes lead groups of rabble\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Minor Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A minor character usually has a name, and has more of a background (and usually more skills) than a stock character or rabble. Minor characters have the following characteristics:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Competency die usually D6 or D8 (D10 or higher for elite characters)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wealth pool based on 2 Social Rank dice plus Competency die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Yield Limit equal to 3 plus the maximum value of their Competency die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wound Limit of 4 (Drop 1, Drop 2, Drop 4, Dying)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Attributes of D6/D8/D10\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Maximum of +2 Specialty Ranks in three Specialties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Three Passions (D10, D8, D6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Two Style Maneuvers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Start with 1 Style Point, with a maximum of 3 Style Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Usually appear singly although often found in groups of minor characters or stock characters as leaders, or as henchpersons of major characters\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Major Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Major characters always have names, and play a key role as opponents (or allies) for the player characters. All should have complex motivations and are built as player characters are built, with just a few exceptions. Characteristics of major characters include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Competency die of D8 or higher, and corresponding experience points spent\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wealth pool based on 2 Social Rank dice plus Competency die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Yield limit equal to 6 plus the maximum value of their Competency die\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wound limit of 5 (Drop 0, Drop 1, Drop 2, Drop 4, Dying)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Attributes of D6/D8/D10\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Maximum of +3 Specialty Ranks (higher for elite characters); built as per player characters with experience points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Four Passions (D12, D10, D8, D6)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Three Style Maneuvers, plus additional if bought with experience points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Start with 3 Style Points, with a maximum of 6 Style Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Are unique individuals in the world\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Have full character sheets as do player characters\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Customizing Opponents\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can adjust opponents to represent other types of characters in the world; for example, a Pirate Crewmember could be used as the basis for an Italian Sailor by changing her Passions.\par}
