{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Creating Major Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As key opponents, major characters should be created to serve specific roles in your game, such as a master villain, a major foil, a powerful ally, or a respected mentor. The recommended method is to build a major opponent in the same way that you\u8217'd create a player character, choosing two classes and so on, and then adding extra experience.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 But sometimes you don\u8217't have the time to do it that way, and you just need to create one simply. Here\u8217's how that works.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab First, come up with an idea of what this character is like, and what kind of role she\u8217'll play in the campaign.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Pick five specialties which she\u8217'll use the most; perhaps Lunge for a duelist or Inspire for a chaplain. These are her primary specialties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Choose another five specialties which are important, but not the focus of her activity. These are secondary specialties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Finally, pick another five tertiary specialties, which are things she can do, but aren\u8217't central to her character.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Assign a D10, D8, and D6 to her attributes in a way that makes sense to you, based on her concept.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Choose how much of a challenge you want to present to your players; this will determine approximately how many experience points she\u8217'll have. Generally speaking, you\u8217'll want a major opponent to have about as many experience points as the sum of all your players, with a minimum of around 20 XP and a maximum around 200.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consult the table, Opponent Creation, and choose one line representing how many experience points your major character will have.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab She will have the listed number of ranks in each of her primary, secondary, and tertiary specialties, as well as competency in the associated skills \u8211- plus Defense, Initiative, Interaction, and Interaction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Assign prowess in two to four types of weapons, zero to two types of armor, and two to four languages, based on your concept.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Pick her social class rank, assign one or more outfits, and equip her with whatever weapons, armor, and other equipment makes the most sense.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Most major characters will have two to four pieces of charmwoven apparel, with a charm die equal to their competency die. These charm dice usually assigned to one of the primary specialties or one of the tertiary ones.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Choose four Passions, assigning them in order from D12 to D6.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Pick three Style Maneuvers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Finally, if she has any additional XP as shown on the table, spend those on whatever else you think might be fun. Extra style maneuvers or specialty ranks in Initiative are always good choices!\sa180\par}
