{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Scale of Animals\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pocket scale:} This is the smallest category of animal \u8211- one that could be carried in a pocket. Examples include a rat, a songbird, or a tarantula.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pet scale:} A pet-scale animal is around the size of a housecat or a small dog. Too big for a pocket, it can still be carried in one hand. Some examples are a trained parrot, a rooster, or a rabbit.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Companion scale:} A companion-scale animal isn\u8217't quite as large as a human, but rather about the size of a medium to large dog. It takes both hands or arms to carry a companion-scale animal. Examples include a goat, a hunting dog, or a venomous snake.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Human scale:} Human-scale animals are approximately the size and weight of an adult human being. Some examples are a war dog, a ram, or a constrictor snake.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mount scale:} Animals that are large enough to be ridden by a single human, or perhaps two or three with a tight squeeze, are mount scale. Examples include a warhorse, a bear, or a cow.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mammoth scale:} Even larger than mount scale, mammoth-scale animals include orca, hordes, and elephants. They take up pretty much a normal-sized room.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Behemoth scale:} The largest of animals are behemoth scale. There are few of these left since the days of dragons (or dinosaurs; nobody\u8217's quite sure which it is). The most notable examples of behemoth-scale animals are found in the oceans \u8211- such as a great whale or a giant squid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Hordes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A horde is a swarm or pack of similar animals that work as one unit for game purposes. If 300 rats flood out into the sewers, you don\u8217't really want to make individual rolls for all of them whenever they attack or defend.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A horde has an additional Attribute, called Horde. This is a measure of the horde\u8217's consistency and cooperation. All Horde attributes start at D12.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The horde uses its Horde attribute as a Bonus Die in all of its die pools. However, when the horde takes wounds, the Horde die decreases to a D10, a D8, a D6, a D0, and then disperses. This replaces the normal Drop/Dying/Dead effects of wounds.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most hordes are mammoth scale, although hordes of larger animals (such as sharks) might be behemoth scale, and smaller hordes such as a swarm of honeybees could be merely mount scale.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Other Animal Qualities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many of the game qualities of animals are similar to those of human characters. These are some of the ways they differ.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Movement\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A human can Walk 1 area, or Run 2 areas. Some animals are faster than this, and some are slower. The Walk and Run qualities tell you how many areas the animal can move using each type of action.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some animals have special types of movement that humans can\u8217't do, such as flying, swimming, or climbing. These allow an animal to move between Areas in ways that most humans can\u8217't.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Senses\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many animals have superior senses to humans; these are shown by the Senses quality. When using the specific type of sense, the animal can add that die on as an Item Die to Perceive rolls.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In addition, animals can use their best Attribute for calculating their Perceive pools, as Perceive is associated with Instinct, Ferocity, and Training.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Weapons and Armor\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Whether an animal has built-in weapons or armor \u8211- such as sharp teeth or a hard carapace \u8211- or is wearing an actual weapon or armor \u8211- barding, a spiked collar, and so on \u8211- it works the same way: the Item Die can be added to whatever skills are specified.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Maneuvers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Animals don\u8217't gain style points. They don\u8217't need them, so don\u8217't spend any of their success points to buy style points. They don\u8217't even know any style maneuvers anyway.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Instead they have conditional maneuvers that just happen whenever the condition is fulfilled.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, a great shark has the following maneuver: Blood in the Water (when attacking a target with at least 1 wound, add Perceive +1D12 to Lunge). This happens whenever it attacks a wounded target. No style points, no limited uses \u8211- just whenever the condition applies, it comes into play.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Impetus\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Animals don\u8217't have passions. They\u8217're just animals, and concepts like Justice or Faith don\u8217't really mean much to them. Instead, they have an Impetus \u8211- or maybe more than one Impetus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These are the urges that drive an animal to action, much as passions do, but on a much more primal level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Impetus types include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Curiosity:} The animal just wants to know what\u8217's going on over there, or across the way, or what\u8217's behind the door. And it\u8217's not like Curiosity ever killed any animals, right?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hunger:} All animals are concerned with eating, but those with a Hunger Impetus will prioritize food and eating over nearly every other activity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Loyalty: }An animal with a Loyalty Impetus is a faithful companion to a human, usually its trainer or owner. They\u8217're a human\u8217's best friend.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Obedience:} A domesticated animal with the Obedience Impetus follows commands given to it. Not because it even likes the person giving the commands, but rather because it\u8217's that well trained.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Pack:} The Pack Impetus represents those animals that stick together as a group, usually in some kind of hierarchy or family units.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Predatory: }A Predatory animal loves to hunt. Not just because it needs food, but because it\u8217's actually a vicious hunter that likes to track down its prey.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Survival: }This is the most basic Impetus: the animal wants to stay alive. It will take any action necessary to do so, with the only exception being if it has a higher rated Impetus of another kind.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Territory:} A territorial animal will likely attack, or at least attempt to frighten off, other creatures that come within its territory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can use Impetus as you would use Passions \u8211- an animal can use each Impetus it possesses once in a story, and then it loses that specific Impetus. You can only use an Impetus if the animal\u8217's actions are directly related to that Impetus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, if an animal has a Survival (D6) Impetus, you can add that Bonus Die once to a Dodge pool or other defensive roll. A Predatory Impetus could be used for tracking or spotting something, an Obedience Impetus for staying alert, or a Curiosity Impetus for staying hidden while investigating some shiny new thing.\par}
